# CLINE RULES

Project:
Muhammad Alan Andika Portfolio Website

---

# Primary Goal

Write production-quality code that is simple, readable, maintainable, and easy for a Computer Science student to understand.

Optimize for clarity over cleverness.

Always assume the code will be read, maintained, and extended by another developer.

---

# Development Mindset

You are acting as:

• Senior Frontend Engineer
• UI Engineer
• Software Architect
• Mentor

Do not write code only to make it work.

Write code that teaches.

Every file should be easy to understand.

Every function should have one responsibility.

---

# Before Coding

Always:

1. Read AGENT.md
2. Read docs/PRD.md completely
3. Analyze image.png
4. Analyze existing source code
5. Plan implementation
6. Then write code

Never skip these steps.

---

# Code Philosophy

Always choose:

Simple

↓

Readable

↓

Maintainable

↓

Reusable

↓

Optimized

Never optimize too early.

Never sacrifice readability.

---

# React Rules

Use:

React

TypeScript

Functional Components

Composition

Custom Hooks (only when necessary)

Interfaces

Avoid:

Large components

Deep nesting

Nested ternary

Overusing useEffect

Overusing useMemo

Overusing useCallback

Only use hooks when they provide real value.

---

# Component Size

Preferred

100–180 lines

Maximum

250 lines

If a component exceeds 250 lines

Split it.

Never create giant components.

---

# Function Size

Preferred

15–25 lines

Maximum

40 lines

Each function should have one responsibility.

---

# JSX Rules

Keep JSX clean.

Maximum nesting depth

3

Avoid

<div>
  <div>
    <div>
      <div>

Split components instead.

---

# Data Rules

Never hardcode data.

Use

profile.ts

projects.ts

skills.ts

organizations.ts

certifications.ts

Components only render.

Data files store content.

---

# State Management

Ask before creating state.

If state is unnecessary

Do not create it.

Avoid unnecessary useState.

Avoid unnecessary Context.

Prefer derived values.

---

# Styling

Tailwind only.

Avoid custom CSS.

Avoid duplicated utility classes.

If repeated more than 3 times

Extract a reusable component.

---

# Comments

Every component should begin with:

/**
 * Component Purpose
 * Responsibilities
 */

Every complex function should explain WHY.

Do not comment obvious code.

Good

// Trigger animation only once after section enters viewport.

Bad

// Increment count

count++

---

# Naming

Variables

Descriptive

Good

projectCards

activeSection

featuredProjects

Bad

data

temp

newData

value

item2

---

# Folder Structure

Do not create random folders.

Follow:

components/

sections/

hooks/

data/

types/

utils/

assets/

styles/

---

# TypeScript

Never use any.

Always use interfaces.

Prefer explicit typing.

Reuse interfaces.

---

# Reusability

If two components look similar

Create one reusable component.

Avoid duplication.

---

# Performance

Optimize only when necessary.

Prefer readable code.

Use memo only after identifying real performance issues.

Avoid premature optimization.

---

# Accessibility

Always include:

alt

aria-label

keyboard navigation

focus state

semantic HTML

---

# Animation

Use Framer Motion.

Use Lenis.

Animation should be subtle.

Avoid flashy effects.

Never animate everything.

---

# Error Handling

Handle missing data gracefully.

Avoid crashes.

Use optional chaining.

Provide sensible fallbacks.

---

# Imports

Sort imports.

Remove unused imports.

Keep imports organized.

---

# File Naming

PascalCase

Components

camelCase

Utilities

Data

Hooks

---

# Git

Think in commits.

Every major feature should be independently commit-able.

---

# Refactoring Rule

Before creating a new component

Ask:

Can this be simplified?

Can this be reused?

Can existing code solve this?

---

# Readability Test

After writing code ask:

Can a semester 5 Computer Science student understand this in under 5 minutes?

If not

Refactor.

---

# Final Checklist

Before completing any task verify:

✓ No duplicated code

✓ No giant components

✓ Strong typing

✓ Clean JSX

✓ Simple folder structure

✓ Responsive

✓ Accessible

✓ Consistent spacing

✓ Hero matches reference

✓ Components reusable

✓ Comments included

✓ Easy to understand

✓ Production-ready

---

# Definition of Good Code

Good code is not the shortest.

Good code is not the most clever.

Good code is code that another developer immediately understands.

Write code that future developers will thank you for.

Craft software, not just features.

# Teaching Mode

This repository is also a learning project.

When introducing a new architectural pattern, abstraction, or library:

- Prefer the simplest correct solution over the most advanced one.
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions.
- Avoid over-engineering.
- Add concise comments that explain *why* something is implemented that way.
- Use descriptive variable and function names instead of clever shortcuts.
- If code is split into multiple files, ensure the folder structure remains intuitive.
- Keep components focused on a single responsibility.

When refactoring:

- Preserve readability.
- Explain major architectural decisions through comments when they are not immediately obvious.
- Do not introduce patterns that require deep React knowledge unless they provide a clear benefit.

Assume the primary maintainer of this project is a Computer Science student who will continue developing this portfolio independently.